There is a moment that arrives for everyone, usually when the machinery of the day has finally gone quiet. You are sitting in a chair, or standing by a window, or watching a particle beam arc across a desert sky, and suddenly you realize that you are watching yourself watch it.

There is the event. There is the body experiencing the event. And then there is the watcher behind the eyes, observing both.

That watcher is the strangest thing in the universe. It is the part of you that feels entirely foreign to the biological machinery it inhabits. It has no weight, no mass, no predictable geometry. It is the silent, observing presence that has remained entirely unchanged since you were five years old, even as every cell in your body has been replaced.

